And, as a scientist, um,
I... I... I'm taken to that belief,

61
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:09,080
because I really believe that's where
the numbers now are leading us.

62
00:05:18,560 --> 00:05:21,000
A couple of years ago, a colleague and I 

63
00:05:21,400 --> 00:05:24,520
tried to take all the amazing data
that we now have,

64
00:05:24,600 --> 00:05:26,280
and we wrote down an equation

65
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:29,080
that allowed us to calculate

66
00:05:29,160 --> 00:05:34,640
the total number of planets out there
that might have civilizations on them.

67
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:40,160
Essentially, what we found
was that there were ten billion...

68
00:05:40,880 --> 00:05:42,080
trillion...

69
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:44,120
planets out there...

70
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:50,040
in the right place where life,
and possibly, civilizations could form.

71
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:00,600
Every one of those planets
is essentially an experiment.

72
00:06:00,680 --> 00:06:04,480
And for none of them, other than ours,
to turn out with a civilization...

73
00:06:05,160 --> 00:06:07,120
that's pushing it quite a bit.

74
00:06:14,120 --> 00:06:18,000
<i>If alien civilizations</i>
<i>are statistically so likely,</i>

75
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:21,280
<i>why haven't astronomers</i>
<i>found any sign of them?</i>

76
00:06:25,120 --> 00:06:26,440
<i>Where is everyone?</i>

77
00:06:29,240 --> 00:06:30,360
Think about it this way.

78
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:35,880
Out there in the Pacific Ocean, there's
187 million billion gallons of water.

79
00:06:35,960 --> 00:06:40,080
Now, if I take this bucket here
and throw it over...

80
00:06:43,400 --> 00:06:44,680
and then haul up, 

81
00:06:45,800 --> 00:06:46,920
see what's in it...

82
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:51,400
All righty. What do we see?

83
00:06:53,240 --> 00:06:54,200
Nothing.

84
00:06:55,720 --> 00:06:58,240
Should I take the fact that I don't see
any life in my bucket 

85
00:06:58,320 --> 00:07:00,520
to tell me that there's no life
in the Pacific Ocean?

86
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:03,880
Well, that would be crazy, right?
There's all kinds of life out there.

87
00:07:03,960 --> 00:07:07,360
There are sea otters, and whales,
and octopuses, and jellyfishes,

88
00:07:07,440 --> 00:07:09,240
and God only knows what's out there.

89
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,640
They're just not in this bucket.

90
00:07:14,240 --> 00:07:16,720
That's why this is a perfect metaphor 

91
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:19,280
for the search
for extraterrestrial intelligence.

92
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:24,240
-[radio telescopes whirring]
-Every time we look at an individual star,

93
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:26,240
that's like dropping a bucket
in the ocean.

94
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:28,760
[radio signals beeping]

95
00:07:28,840 --> 00:07:31,280
We're going to have to look
at a lot of stars,

96
00:07:31,360 --> 00:07:34,160
and we're gonna have
to search through a lot of data...

97
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:39,040
until we find the clue that leads us
to another civilization.

98
00:07:53,400 --> 00:07:59,520
<i>What sort of alien civilizations</i>
<i>might exist in the vastness of space?</i>

99
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:10,520
<i>Imagine a planet nine billion years old,</i>

100
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:13,040
<i>twice as old as Earth.</i>

101
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:18,600
<i>Old enough that a truly advanced</i>
<i>intelligence could evolve.</i>

102
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:24,600
<i>This is Terra.</i>

103
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:34,280
<i>It was once a fertile world.</i>

104
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:38,080
<i>Now, it is barren.</i>

105
00:08:39,640 --> 00:08:42,640
<i>But life can still thrive here...</i>

106
00:08:45,040 --> 00:08:47,280
<i>in artificial domes.</i>

107
00:08:52,120 --> 00:08:54,360
[spaceships whirring]

108
00:08:57,480 --> 00:09:01,080
<i>Plants convert sunlight</i>
<i>into glucose energy...</i>

109
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:06,000
<i>which feeds the inhabitants of Terra.</i>

110
00:09:09,680 --> 00:09:12,040
[mechanism buzzes]

111
00:09:16,520 --> 00:09:22,040
<i>Each box contains the brain matter</i>
<i>of a super-intelligent being.</i>

112
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:28,000
<i>Over time, they've evolved</i>
<i>not to need their bodies.</i>

113
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:33,200
<i>They exist only as neural tissue.</i>

114
00:09:38,880 --> 00:09:41,680
<i>They never age.</i> <i>They never die.</i>

115
00:09:42,440 --> 00:09:45,640
<i>They're monitored</i>
<i>and maintained by robots.</i>

116
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:51,440
<i>Each is an individual.</i>

117
00:09:53,240 --> 00:09:56,280
<i>But they're connected to think as one.</i>

118
00:09:57,120 --> 00:09:58,760
<i>A hive mind.</i>

119
00:10:00,760 --> 00:10:02,160
[radio signals beeping]

120
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:06,120
<i>This is a hyper-advanced civilization.</i>

121
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:08,200
[signals continue]

122
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:11,760
[overlapping garbled voice transmissions]

123
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:21,080
<i>On Earth, humans are the only species</i>
<i>to have created any form of civilization.</i>

124
00:10:21,160 --> 00:10:22,880
[indistinct human radio transmissions]

125
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:29,200
<i>Why haven't other intelligent creatures</i>
<i>done the same thing?</i>

126
00:10:38,440 --> 00:10:42,080
<i>The octopus is as close</i>
<i>to an alien intelligence</i>

127
00:10:42,160 --> 00:10:44,200
<i>as exists on our planet.</i>

128
00:10:51,960 --> 00:10:54,800
[woman] Octopuses belong
to a group called cephalopods.

129
00:10:57,040 --> 00:10:59,960
And they have evolved down
a completely different pathway.

130
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:08,520
The octopus has separate nervous systems
in each of its arms.

131
00:11:09,720 --> 00:11:12,640
So, each arm contains
about 14 million neurons.

132
00:11:13,320 --> 00:11:16,120
And each arm
can make independent decisions.

133
00:11:17,040 --> 00:11:21,320
So the octopus can be said to have,
essentially, nine separate brains.

134
00:11:25,480 --> 00:11:27,640
I kind of wanna reach out and touch him.

135
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:29,000
[chuckles]

136
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:35,880
Lego toys are quite hard to get apart.

137
00:11:37,040 --> 00:11:40,160
But we're curious to see
if he's gonna be able to open them.

138
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:10,200
<i>Octopuses are clearly smart.</i>

139
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:17,360
<i>But being smart isn't enough</i>
<i>to form a civilization.</i>

140
00:12:28,040 --> 00:12:30,360
<i>The key is cooperation...</i>

141
00:12:32,200 --> 00:12:34,080
<i>sharing ideas...</i>

142
00:12:35,760 --> 00:12:41,040
<i>passing down knowledge</i>
<i>from one generation to the next.</i>

143
00:12:45,120 --> 00:12:47,640
