is constantly improving.

144
00:12:48,600 --> 00:12:51,680
We keep building
on each other's inventions.

145
00:12:55,840 --> 00:12:56,880
All right.

146
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:02,160
Take this taxi, for example.

147
00:13:03,040 --> 00:13:06,400
Wheels were invented more
than five-and-a-half thousand years ago.

148
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:10,560
Iron has been smelted more than
four-and-a-half thousand years ago.

149
00:13:12,440 --> 00:13:16,800
Vulcanized rubber has been used for tires
since about 180 years.

150
00:13:19,360 --> 00:13:21,360
So, all of these inventions were necessary

151
00:13:21,440 --> 00:13:24,200
to actually build
something as complicated as this car.

152
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:31,760
An octopus, by comparison, has to pretty
much figure out everything for himself.

153
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:37,280
There is no improving and building
on previous solutions.

154
00:13:37,840 --> 00:13:40,680
And that's pretty limiting,
even if you have nine brains.

155
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:48,400
<i>Civilizations are like living organisms...</i>

156
00:13:50,240 --> 00:13:52,480
<i>with millions of connected parts.</i>

157
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:57,560
<i>It's this connectivity</i>

158
00:13:58,120 --> 00:14:00,240
<i>that allows them to grow.</i>

159
00:14:12,120 --> 00:14:16,080
<i>But the civilization on Terra is in peril.</i>

160
00:14:19,520 --> 00:14:22,800
<i>Its star is double the age</i>
<i>of our own sun.</i>

161
00:14:28,080 --> 00:14:32,760
<i>And as stars get older,</i>
<i>they burn bigger and brighter.</i>

162
00:14:37,680 --> 00:14:42,040
<i>Eventually, the planet Terra</i>
<i>will be incinerated.</i>

163
00:14:48,920 --> 00:14:51,680
<i>So an escape plan is underway...</i>

164
00:14:56,440 --> 00:15:00,200
<i>to colonize another planet</i>
<i>in the same solar system...</i>

165
00:15:03,160 --> 00:15:05,440
<i>further from the star than Terra.</i>

166
00:15:12,920 --> 00:15:16,600
<i>There's ice on this world,</i>
<i>but no atmosphere.</i>

167
00:15:19,640 --> 00:15:22,280
<i>It needs to be manufactured.</i>

168
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:37,800
<i>This is engineering on a planetary scale.</i>

169
00:15:40,360 --> 00:15:42,200
[machines hissing]

170
00:15:42,320 --> 00:15:45,280
<i>Giant machines melt the ice caps</i>

171
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:48,360
<i>to release vapor and gas...</i>

172
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:52,840
[energy beams roaring]

173
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:56,600
<i>...generating enough atmosphere</i>
<i>to warm the planet.</i>

174
00:16:00,920 --> 00:16:06,120
<i>Such a massive project</i>
<i>requires a massive amount of energy...</i>

175
00:16:08,480 --> 00:16:12,160
<i>delivered directly from the aging star.</i>

176
00:16:14,360 --> 00:16:19,160
[star rumbling]

177
00:16:24,120 --> 00:16:30,080
<i>The ability to harness energy</i>
<i>is the bedrock of civilization itself.</i>

178
00:16:34,480 --> 00:16:38,960
[traditional Far Eastern music playing]

179
00:16:45,120 --> 00:16:47,960
[man] Part of what I do
is to try and predict the future.

180
00:16:48,640 --> 00:16:52,960
And you can look back in history
and get a lot of ideas from there,

181
00:16:54,240 --> 00:16:59,280
but there are underlying trends we can use
to some extent to see what's to come,

182
00:17:00,440 --> 00:17:03,600
like life expectancy, wealth,
population size.

183
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:08,840
And one of the most revealing is the
amount of energy that civilizations use.

184
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:14,880
<i>The more energy a civilization can access,</i>

185
00:17:15,440 --> 00:17:17,600
<i>the more powerful it becomes.</i>

186
00:17:20,040 --> 00:17:22,480
<i>That's the secret of progress...</i>

187
00:17:24,040 --> 00:17:26,720
<i>from the Stone Age until today.</i>

188
00:17:39,400 --> 00:17:42,400
So, unleashing the heat and energy
in charcoal 

189
00:17:42,480 --> 00:17:46,080
allowed us to get temperatures
hot enough to smelt metals 

190
00:17:46,160 --> 00:17:48,040
to make tools and weapons.

191
00:17:52,040 --> 00:17:56,680
Later on, of course, we harnessed
fossil fuels like coal and gas,

192
00:17:57,200 --> 00:18:00,600
allowing the creation of vehicles
that could hurtle us across the world

193
00:18:00,680 --> 00:18:03,640
at much higher speed
than we ever had before.

194
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:16,080
But the greatest source of energy
is, of course, our star.

195
00:18:22,840 --> 00:18:25,320
[radio waves oscillating]

196
00:18:36,640 --> 00:18:42,880
<i>The Noor Power Station is the largest</i>
<i>solar complex of its kind in the world.</i>

197
00:18:48,080 --> 00:18:52,400
<i>Half a million mirrors</i>
<i>at the edge of the Sahara Desert.</i>

198
