<i>bigger and brighter...</i>

231
00:21:43,840 --> 00:21:46,800
<i>it also becomes more volatile.</i>

232
00:21:51,160 --> 00:21:52,880
[high-pitched whirring]

233
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:54,320
<i>A solar flare.</i>

234
00:21:59,720 --> 00:22:03,400
[energy roaring]

235
00:22:03,480 --> 00:22:06,680
[energy crackling]

236
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:15,560
<i>Sooner or later, this will be</i>
<i>the destiny of Terra itself...</i>

237
00:22:18,280 --> 00:22:21,720
<i>to be swept away by the power of its sun.</i>

238
00:22:27,920 --> 00:22:33,680
<i>The solution is to colonize</i>
<i>the new planet as quickly as possible.</i>

239
00:22:35,280 --> 00:22:38,920
[machines hissing]

240
00:22:39,040 --> 00:22:40,880
<i>There are no life forms here.</i>

241
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:45,040
<i>All the work is done by machines.</i>

242
00:22:45,120 --> 00:22:48,360
[energy beams roaring]

243
00:22:49,120 --> 00:22:51,040
[spaceship whirring]

244
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:55,920
<i>They're able to think for themselves</i>
<i>and make their own decisions.</i>

245
00:22:58,720 --> 00:22:59,760
[spaceships whirring]

246
00:22:59,840 --> 00:23:02,200
<i>They are artificially intelligent.</i>

247
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:11,240
[indistinct vocal transmission]

248
00:23:11,320 --> 00:23:14,320
<i>If humans are to form colonies in space,</i>

249
00:23:14,400 --> 00:23:17,440
<i>the groundwork will be done</i>
<i>in the same way...</i>

250
00:23:20,160 --> 00:23:22,000
<i>using robots.</i>

251
00:23:26,120 --> 00:23:28,360
<i>And those robots will be designed</i>

252
00:23:29,240 --> 00:23:31,280
<i>by people like Philip Metzger.</i>

253
00:23:33,840 --> 00:23:37,680
<i>He has spent his whole life</i>
<i>in and around the space program.</i>

254
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:42,640
[Philip] My father used to work
in this building,

255
00:23:42,720 --> 00:23:45,000
and he helped build the Saturn V rockets 

256
00:23:45,080 --> 00:23:48,040
that were large enough
to take humans to the moon.

257
00:23:48,680 --> 00:23:51,520
[man 1] <i>Apollo 11,</i>
<i>this is the launch operations manager.</i>

258
00:23:51,600 --> 00:23:54,080
<i>The launch team wishes you</i>
<i>good luck and Godspeed.</i>

259
00:23:54,840 --> 00:23:57,400
[man 2] <i>Ah, thank you very much.</i>
<i>Know it will be a good one.</i>

260
00:24:03,440 --> 00:24:06,160
[Philip] I'll never forget
the Apollo 11 flight.

261
00:24:09,320 --> 00:24:11,160
I was seven years old.

262
00:24:11,720 --> 00:24:14,720
I was across the river during the launch,
watching it.

263
00:24:16,040 --> 00:24:17,960
There were helicopters flying around.

264
00:24:19,120 --> 00:24:20,880
People had come from all over the world,

265
00:24:21,280 --> 00:24:24,320
-coming to watch the moon launch.
-[cheering and whistling]

266
00:24:24,400 --> 00:24:25,800
It was electric.

267
00:24:25,880 --> 00:24:29,920
[man 1] <i>Astronauts report it feels good.</i>
<i>20 seconds and counting.</i>

268
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:31,200
[radio static crackling]

269
00:24:31,280 --> 00:24:34,080
<i>T minus 15 seconds, guidance is internal.</i>

270
00:24:34,840 --> 00:24:36,640
<i>Twelve, eleven,</i>

271
00:24:36,720 --> 00:24:38,840
<i>ten, nine...</i>

272
00:24:38,920 --> 00:24:40,720
<i>Ignition sequence starts.</i>

273
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:43,320
<i>...six... five... four...</i>

274
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:46,160
<i>three... two... one...</i>

275
00:24:46,800 --> 00:24:47,760
<i>zero.</i>

276
00:24:47,840 --> 00:24:50,920
[booster rockets roar]

277
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:51,960
<i>Liftoff!</i>

278
00:24:52,040 --> 00:24:53,520
<i>We have a liftoff.</i>

279
00:25:01,640 --> 00:25:06,280
As it climbed into the sky,
you could see that long, beautiful flame

280
00:25:06,360 --> 00:25:08,800
shimmering across the water.

281
00:25:11,320 --> 00:25:12,920
[man 2] <i>We got skirts-up?</i> 

282
00:25:13,680 --> 00:25:15,320
[man 3] <i>Roger, we confirm skirts-up.</i>

283
00:25:15,400 --> 00:25:16,480
[radio beeps]

284
00:25:17,840 --> 00:25:22,280
[Philip] So, I grew up wanting to be
a rocket scientist, my entire life.

285
00:25:36,720 --> 00:25:39,240
[narrator] <i>Philip became a NASA scientist.</i>

286
00:25:40,720 --> 00:25:42,920
<i>But rather than sticking at rocket design,</i>

287
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:46,320
<i>he moved into robotics.</i>

288
00:25:52,040 --> 00:25:55,280
[Philip] If we ever really want to do
anything fabulous in space,

289
00:25:55,360 --> 00:25:56,880
we need robots.

290
00:26:05,760 --> 00:26:09,360
RASSOR is designed to work
in tough planetary environments.

291
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:14,160
-It can climb over rocks.
-[robot whirs]

292
00:26:14,240 --> 00:26:17,480
If it gets stuck,
it can get itself unstuck.

293
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:23,240
If it flips upside down,
it can flip itself over.

294
00:26:24,240 --> 00:26:26,920
In any situation,
it can get itself out of trouble.

295
00:26:29,520 --> 00:26:33,240
The simplest thing that we could mine
on a planet is the regolith,

296
00:26:33,840 --> 00:26:36,680
the dirt that covers
the planetary surface.

297
00:26:38,640 --> 00:26:40,960
You can extract metal from the regolith.

298
00:26:42,720 --> 00:26:47,480
You can also make ceramics that are used
for insulating electrical systems.

299
00:26:48,480 --> 00:26:50,480
And you can make rocket fuel.

300
00:26:53,520 --> 00:26:56,280
But mining does take intelligence.

301
00:26:58,120 --> 00:27:00,800
You have to know where to drive,
where to cut.

302
00:27:01,400 --> 00:27:04,360
You've gotta keep from getting lost,
get yourself unstuck.

303
00:27:04,440 --> 00:27:07,360
So it's going to take a clever machine
like RASSOR

304
00:27:07,440 --> 00:27:09,960
to be able to start industry in space.

305
00:27:12,240 --> 00:27:15,880
<i>The Holy Grail of robotics</i>
<i>is self-replication...</i>

306
00:27:17,680 --> 00:27:20,280
<i>a machine that can make copies of itself.</i>

307
00:27:23,480 --> 00:27:26,480
This is a spare wheel for RASSOR.

308
00:27:27,200 --> 00:27:33,600
A robot part made by a robot
for another robot, using space materials.<i> </i>

309
00:27:34,680 --> 00:27:37,600
But this is an early example
of how we're evolving the robots

310
00:27:37,680 --> 00:27:44,400
toward a fully closed ecology of robots
that can self-reproduce in space.

311
00:27:50,520 --> 00:27:54,840
Once you've got self-reproducing robots,
everywhere is a place you can go.

312
00:27:55,920 --> 00:27:58,000
I don't think there are any limits.

313
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:10,520
[spaceship whirring]

314
00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:14,600
<i>Without input from any life</i> <i>form,</i>

315
00:28:15,840 --> 00:28:18,560
<i>the robots are re-engineering a planet...</i>

316
00:28:21,520 --> 00:28:23,720
<i>making it ready for colonization.</i>

317
00:28:26,360 --> 00:28:28,360
[spaceships whirring]

318
00:28:34,840 --> 00:28:37,400
<i>Now, it's time to abandon Terra.</i>

319
00:28:41,240 --> 00:28:44,240
<i>Each of the domes has been designed</i>
<i>for this moment...</i>

320
00:28:47,040 --> 00:28:49,080
<i>to get into orbit.</i>

321
00:28:53,840 --> 00:28:57,080
<i>From here, they will travel</i>
<i>to their new home.</i>

322
00:29:04,040 --> 00:29:06,040
[mechanical whooshing]

323
00:29:12,040 --> 00:29:15,720
<i>The domes have their own</i>
<i>life-support systems.</i>

324
00:29:17,720 --> 00:29:19,520
<i>But they're helpless</i>

325
00:29:20,120 --> 00:29:23,400
<i>against a high-energy burst</i>
<i>of solar radiation.</i>

326
00:29:23,480 --> 00:29:25,480
[star rumbling, hissing]

327
00:29:27,040 --> 00:29:31,080
[mechanical systems powering down]

328
00:29:31,200 --> 00:29:32,600
[rapid beeping]

329
00:29:32,680 --> 00:29:34,280
[object crashing]

330
00:29:48,960 --> 00:29:53,400
<i>Nothing is evolved to survive</i>
<i>in the vacuum of space.</i>

331
00:29:57,200 --> 00:29:58,960
[insects chirping]

332
00:29:59,040 --> 00:30:03,080
<i>This is as true for aliens</i>
<i>as it is for humans.</i>

333
00:30:11,320 --> 00:30:15,520
<i>Michael Foale knows all about</i>
<i>the dangers of space travel.</i>

334
00:30:20,040 --> 00:30:26,640
<i>In 1997, he was a guest American astronaut</i>
<i>on the Russian Mir space station...</i>

335
00:30:29,760 --> 00:30:32,680
<i>during the first collision in space.</i>

336
00:30:37,840 --> 00:30:40,960
[Michael] There was, uh, an attempt
by the Russian commander, Vasily,

337
00:30:41,040 --> 00:30:44,760
and his crewmate<i> </i>to control
a cargo ship that weighed seven tons,

338
00:30:44,840 --> 00:30:46,760
and dock it without the radar,

339
00:30:46,840 --> 00:30:49,840
without speed,
without distance measurements...

340
00:30:49,920 --> 00:30:51,760
Dock it to our space station.

341
00:30:54,240 --> 00:30:58,880
[indistinct Russian radio transmissions]

342
00:31:06,920 --> 00:31:08,200
[Michael] I felt the station...

343
00:31:08,680 --> 00:31:12,840
I didn't "felt" it, I <i>saw</i> the station
move all around me and I heard a thud.

344
00:31:12,920 --> 00:31:14,680
[beeping]

345
00:31:19,880 --> 00:31:23,920
And at that point I thought, "Mm...
This could be it, you know, where I die."

346
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:26,280
Uh, 'cause I'm looking at all these bolts 

347
00:31:26,360 --> 00:31:28,560
and I was just waiting
for those bolts to part,

348
00:31:28,640 --> 00:31:31,440
and to, kind of, rip open
and just see the vacuum of space.

349
00:31:38,600 --> 00:31:41,840
And then, all the fans, all the lights,

350
00:31:42,360 --> 00:31:45,240
all the computers failed and went silent.

351
00:31:49,720 --> 00:31:52,480
And now we're in
a completely silent station

352
00:31:53,120 --> 00:31:54,600
that's getting cold.

353
00:31:59,400 --> 00:32:02,080
[radio transmissions in Russian]
<i>We've lost power.</i>

354
00:32:03,160 --> 00:32:06,880
<i>Pressure is at 602.</i>

355
00:32:06,960 --> 00:32:09,440
[breathing]

356
00:32:09,520 --> 00:32:11,680
And then my ears started to pop.

357
00:32:13,480 --> 00:32:15,120
I knew we were depressurizing,

358
00:32:16,520 --> 00:32:19,240
and that basically,
air was leaving the space station,

359
00:32:20,800 --> 00:32:22,920
and we only had 23 minutes left to live,

360
00:32:23,000 --> 00:32:25,520
if we stayed there
and we didn't stop the leak.

361
00:32:26,880 --> 00:32:29,480
I started helping Sasha
pull these cables out.

362
00:32:30,840 --> 00:32:33,640
Huge cables I thought would have taken
us hours to undo,

363
00:32:33,720 --> 00:32:35,080
we did them in six minutes.

364
00:32:35,720 --> 00:32:39,960
And we'd take this cap and we'd put it in
and it sucks in, and it goes... "pew."

365
00:32:40,040 --> 00:32:41,960
And at that point, we've stopped the leak.

366
00:32:47,240 --> 00:32:50,320
And it was there in front of the window,
looking at the galaxy...

367
00:32:51,680 --> 00:32:52,680
I said...

368
00:32:53,320 --> 00:32:58,360
"Well, I know it's been a really bad day,
but this is an amazingly beautiful view."

369
00:33:01,120 --> 00:33:04,200
You're kind of sensing, trying to sense
all of the, uh...

370
00:33:04,280 --> 00:33:06,360
The presence in the... in the universe.

371
00:33:14,360 --> 00:33:19,200
<i>In total, Michael Foale went into space</i>
<i>on six missions.</i>

372
00:33:19,680 --> 00:33:21,440
Oops, more hair going away.

373
00:33:24,040 --> 00:33:26,480
<i>But every second spent off-world</i>

374
00:33:27,520 --> 00:33:30,000
<i>-increased his dose of radiation.</i>
-[radio chatter]

375
00:33:33,440 --> 00:33:35,520
[Michael] We're exposed
to radiation on Earth,

376
00:33:36,520 --> 00:33:38,400
but once you go into orbit,

377
00:33:38,480 --> 00:33:41,480
now you're exposed
to thousands of times more radiation.

378
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:47,880
And that radiation now is damaging
our DNA much faster,

379
00:33:48,720 --> 00:33:52,320
and the repair mechanisms
that we evolved to have

380
00:33:52,400 --> 00:33:54,280
are not able to cope with it.

381
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:16,920
When I came back from my space flights,

382
00:34:17,480 --> 00:34:22,720
they found I had, like, four percent
of my white blood cells had DNA mutations.

383
00:34:28,080 --> 00:34:32,320
Most of those mutated cells get killed
by other white blood cells in your body,

384
00:34:34,280 --> 00:34:36,440
but, some of them,
unfortunately, don't die.

385
00:34:37,800 --> 00:34:41,320
They reproduce and mutate
and become cancers.

386
00:34:42,600 --> 00:34:45,600
That is a fundamental risk for astronauts.

387
00:34:52,920 --> 00:34:55,880
And if we imagine going out to stars,

388
00:34:55,960 --> 00:35:00,000
it could be that, out of a hundred ships,
only one of them makes it.

389
00:35:06,840 --> 00:35:08,960
[loud whooshing]

390
00:35:12,480 --> 00:35:15,880
<i>Long-distance space travel</i>
<i>will always be risky...</i>

391
00:35:18,080 --> 00:35:20,080
<i>even for intelligent aliens.</i>

392
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:26,360
<i>There's no protection against</i>
<i>a sudden blast of stellar radiation.</i>

393
00:35:35,560 --> 00:35:38,280
<i>But for those that make it</i>
<i>to the end of the journey,</i>

394
00:35:39,440 --> 00:35:41,320
<i>this is their reward...</i>

395
00:35:43,800 --> 00:35:45,520
<i>a new Terra.</i>

396
00:35:56,520 --> 00:35:59,320
<i>Rather than adapting to a different world,</i>

397
00:36:00,640 --> 00:36:03,800
<i>they have created a copy</i>
<i>of their old world.</i>

398
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:11,560
<i>Such are the benefits</i>
<i>of an advanced civilization.</i>

399
00:36:18,320 --> 00:36:20,320
[radio signals beeping]

400
00:36:21,960 --> 00:36:24,640
<i>But how long will the good times last?</i>

401
00:36:28,720 --> 00:36:33,000
<i>The star keeps growing,</i>
<i>bigger and brighter...</i>

402
00:36:34,280 --> 00:36:36,280
<i>spitting out more radiation.</i>

403
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:40,440
[star roaring]

404
00:36:42,400 --> 00:36:47,200
<i>Eventually, it will render the new planet</i>
<i>as lifeless as Terra.</i>

405
00:36:57,320 --> 00:36:59,840
<i>And then they'll need to relocate again,</i>

406
00:37:01,080 --> 00:37:04,000
<i>to another planet, further from the star.</i>

407
00:37:15,240 --> 00:37:18,200
<i>This is the advantage of being mobile.</i>

408
00:37:20,520 --> 00:37:23,880
<i>It's possible to transit</i>
<i>from world to world,</i>

409
00:37:24,400 --> 00:37:27,200
<i>making and remaking home.</i>

410
00:37:39,480 --> 00:37:44,640
<i>Perhaps there's an alien civilization</i>
<i>already headed for Earth.</i>

411
00:37:48,120 --> 00:37:50,600
<i>If so, should we hide from them,</i>

412
00:37:51,440 --> 00:37:53,240
<i>or make ourselves known?</i>

413
00:37:57,560 --> 00:37:58,840
Okay. Um...

414
00:37:59,720 --> 00:38:01,880
Let me... Let me end by saying...

415
00:38:03,120 --> 00:38:07,200
Let me close by telling you
why we should begin transmitting

416
00:38:07,280 --> 00:38:09,920
and why we should begin right now.

417
00:38:12,240 --> 00:38:13,720
[exhales]

418
00:38:16,920 --> 00:38:21,800
<i>Doug Vakoch wants to open up a dialogue</i>
<i>with potential aliens</i>

419
00:38:22,480 --> 00:38:25,000
<i>by sending them radio messages.</i>

420
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:31,840
[elevator dings]

421
00:38:37,520 --> 00:38:40,720
<i>But first, he needs to persuade</i>
<i>astronomers on Earth</i>

422
00:38:41,920 --> 00:38:43,480
<i>that it's a good idea.</i>

423
00:38:43,560 --> 00:38:45,560
[crowd applauding]

424
00:38:51,680 --> 00:38:53,480
[Doug] This is where it all started.

425
00:38:55,640 --> 00:38:59,400
The biggest radio telescope
Earth had ever seen.

426
00:39:13,240 --> 00:39:15,280
There's something about being here,

427
00:39:16,480 --> 00:39:18,920
the awesomeness, the scale of the place.

428
00:39:27,040 --> 00:39:32,080
This is where, in 1974, we sent
humanity's first message into space.

429
00:39:37,120 --> 00:39:39,200
[long beep]

430
00:39:40,800 --> 00:39:45,880
It starts by these pulses that count out
the numbers from one through ten.

431
00:39:46,440 --> 00:39:48,200
[bleeping]

432
00:39:48,920 --> 00:39:51,280
Then after we've shown extraterrestrials
how we count,

433
00:39:51,360 --> 00:39:53,280
we use those numbers to describe

434
00:39:53,360 --> 00:39:56,280
some of the chemical elements
essential to life on Earth.

435
00:39:56,360 --> 00:39:58,440
[beeping continues]

436
00:39:58,520 --> 00:40:00,080
And then after that...

437
00:40:01,040 --> 00:40:02,720
what we look like,

438
00:40:03,640 --> 00:40:05,480
how many humans there are,

439
00:40:06,040 --> 00:40:07,240
how tall we are.

440
00:40:09,040 --> 00:40:12,000
Then after that,
a representation of our solar system.

441
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:17,000
And then it ends with a representation
of this telescope itself,

442
00:40:17,080 --> 00:40:18,600
where the message came from.

443
00:40:18,680 --> 00:40:20,280
[rapid bleeping]

444
00:40:21,600 --> 00:40:24,040
<i>The pulses of the Arecibo message</i>

445
00:40:24,120 --> 00:40:26,400
<i>could be arranged into a pictogram</i>

446
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:31,240
<i>to inform intelligent aliens</i>
<i>about life on Earth.</i>

447
00:40:35,240 --> 00:40:37,760
[oscillating frequency hums]

448
00:40:38,520 --> 00:40:40,080
<i>But it was a one-time event,</i>

449
00:40:40,920 --> 00:40:45,880
<i>aimed at a star cluster</i>
<i>25,000 light-years away.</i>

450
00:40:50,120 --> 00:40:52,600
[Doug] If we'd been sending messages
to nearby stars

451
00:40:52,680 --> 00:40:54,840
at the same time
we sent out the Arecibo message,

452
00:40:54,920 --> 00:40:59,400
we could be getting responses today
from any of thousands of stars.

453
00:41:00,760 --> 00:41:03,480
But we haven't, and so we're in the dark.

454
00:41:06,320 --> 00:41:10,560
The biggest reason we haven't sent
more messages is because we're afraid.

455
00:41:11,760 --> 00:41:15,040
Because the blockbuster
science-fiction films 

456
00:41:15,120 --> 00:41:17,880
show aliens coming to Earth
and annihilating us...

457
00:41:20,920 --> 00:41:23,280
and so that's what we think
would really happen.

458
00:41:27,240 --> 00:41:31,960
I think the... the most prominent challenge
is the concern that some people have

459
00:41:32,040 --> 00:41:37,520
that transmitting intentional messages,
uh, will lead to an alien invasion.

460
00:41:37,920 --> 00:41:40,000
And I think the easiest
response to that is,

461
00:41:40,080 --> 00:41:44,280
our planet has been giving off evidence
of life for two billion years.

462
00:41:44,800 --> 00:41:47,240
So, if there are any really paranoid
aliens out there 

463
00:41:47,320 --> 00:41:49,560
who want to annihilate any competition,

464
00:41:49,640 --> 00:41:52,200
they've had a long time to come here,
and I haven't seen 'em.

465
00:41:56,440 --> 00:41:59,280
<i>Rather than sending an occasional message</i>
<i>into space,</i>

466
00:42:00,440 --> 00:42:03,400
<i>Doug's plan is to transmit</i>
<i>thousands of them...</i>

467
00:42:05,800 --> 00:42:08,600
<i>when the Arecibo telescope</i>
<i>is on downtime.</i>

468
00:42:12,640 --> 00:42:15,600
[Doug] With radio astronomy,
you can do it any time of the day.

469
00:42:16,320 --> 00:42:18,600
But... I like to do it at night.

470
00:42:21,560 --> 00:42:23,920
Caffeine is essential for astronomers.
Um...

471
00:42:24,760 --> 00:42:28,120
A lot of late nights in the observations
and we have to stay sharp.

472
00:42:34,880 --> 00:42:36,360
[radio signals beeping]

473
00:42:36,440 --> 00:42:41,440
Once a month, Arecibo does a survey
of recently discovered asteroids.

474
00:42:44,040 --> 00:42:46,800
Quite often there's a gap, maybe an hour,

475
00:42:46,880 --> 00:42:50,640
where the transmitter is transmitting
off into space at no particular place.

476
00:42:54,280 --> 00:42:56,560
-[cicadas chirping]
-[bleeping continues]

477
00:42:56,640 --> 00:43:01,560
What I'm proposing is that Arecibo
should use those gaps in the schedule

478
00:43:02,040 --> 00:43:05,320
to target nearby stars with a message,

479
00:43:05,400 --> 00:43:08,880
in case there are any extraterrestrials
in orbit around that star.

480
00:43:13,120 --> 00:43:17,240
Each month, we could be targeting
about 50 stars 

481
00:43:17,680 --> 00:43:20,080
that may support intelligent life. 

482
00:43:20,160 --> 00:43:23,040
And for me, it's a no-brainer.
I think we should be doing it.

483
00:43:26,160 --> 00:43:29,320
I think of this in terms
of what's sometimes called

484
00:43:29,400 --> 00:43:31,040
"joining the galactic club."

485
00:43:31,720 --> 00:43:36,760
And what I find so strange about that
analogy is that no one ever talks about,

486
00:43:36,840 --> 00:43:40,280
um, paying our dues
or even submitting an application.

487
00:43:40,360 --> 00:43:43,680
And that's what messaging
extraterrestrial intelligence does.

488
00:43:43,760 --> 00:43:46,520
It may just be our way
of making first contact.

489
00:43:46,960 --> 00:43:47,800
Thanks.

490
00:43:47,880 --> 00:43:51,040
[woman] Thank you very much to Doug
for this interesting presentation. 

491
00:43:53,400 --> 00:43:55,400
[cicadas chirping]

492
00:44:00,120 --> 00:44:04,080
[Doug] When we reach out to other stars,
when we send them our messages,

493
00:44:05,520 --> 00:44:10,600
in the best-case scenario,
we get a reply back in 10 or 20 years.

494
00:44:12,720 --> 00:44:16,560
But realistically, it could take
thousands of years.

495
00:44:21,040 --> 00:44:23,360
So this is something that we're doing,

496
00:44:23,800 --> 00:44:28,480
not for ourselves, but for our children,
for our grandchildren.

497
00:44:29,560 --> 00:44:31,080
And even for the aliens.

498
00:44:34,280 --> 00:44:37,160
[woman] <i>Eight, seven, six,</i>

499
00:44:37,240 --> 00:44:40,200
<i>five, four, three,</i>

500
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:42,360
<i>two, one.</i>

501
00:44:43,680 --> 00:44:45,320
<i>Mission liftoff.</i> 

502
00:44:45,440 --> 00:44:47,440
[engines hiss]

503
00:44:50,760 --> 00:44:52,440
[man] <i>Switching down range.</i>

504
00:44:52,520 --> 00:44:58,760
[narrator] <i>In 2018, the latest</i>
<i>planet-hunting telescope went into orbit.</i>

505
00:45:04,600 --> 00:45:07,160
[clicking, whirring]

506
00:45:07,840 --> 00:45:10,680
<i>It is finding evidence of new worlds</i>

507
00:45:11,960 --> 00:45:13,760
<i>across the night sky.</i>

508
00:45:23,520 --> 00:45:26,520
<i>Astronomers think it's only</i>
<i>a matter of time</i>

509
00:45:26,920 --> 00:45:30,000
<i>before some alien life forms</i>
<i>are discovered.</i>

510
00:45:35,520 --> 00:45:39,360
<i>Among them, perhaps, intelligent beings.</i>

511
00:45:45,120 --> 00:45:47,680
<i>One day, we will know for sure.</i>

512
00:45:51,920 --> 00:45:57,800
<i>Until then, we can only guess</i>
<i>at who or what is out there.</i>

